{"title_page": "Bereans", "text_new": "In ancient times, the '''Bereans''' were the inhabitants of the city of [[Berea (Bible)|Berea]], also known in the [[Bible]] as Beroea, now known as [[Veria]] in what is today Greek Macedonia, [[Early centers of Christianity#Greece|northern Greece]]. The name has been taken up by certain [[Protestant]] groups.\n\n==Biblical context==\n\nAccording to the [[Book of Acts]], Chapter 17 verse 11, [[Paul of Tarsus]] and [[Silas]] preached at [[Berea (Bible)|Berea]], and the inhabitants \"... received the word with all readiness of mind, and searched the scriptures daily, whether those things were so.\",<ref>[http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=acts%2017:11&version=KJV Acts 17:11] [[King James Bible]]</ref> and many of them believed.\n\n==Modern use==\nHistorically, the Bereans (also called Beroeans, Barclayans or Barclayites) were a Protestant sect following former Scottish [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]] minister [[John Barclay (1734-1798)]]. Founded in [[Edinburgh]] in 1773, the Berean Church followed a modified form of [[Calvinism]]. It had congregations in [[Scotland]], [[London]] and [[Bristol]], but mainly merged with the [[Congregationalists#United Kingdom|Congregationalists]] after Barclay's death in 1798.\n\nA new Protestant Christian group began in the 1850s in the United States under the tutelage of Dr. John Thomas. The name \"[[Christadelphian]]\" was chosen as it is believed that those who believe and obey the [[Law of Christ|Commandments of Christ]] and the Bible as the inspired word of God, are \"Brethren in Christ\". The original group split, with one group continuing with the name \"The Christadelphians\" and the second group adding the word \"Berean\" to become the \"[[Berean Christadelphians]]\". The word \"Berean\" was chosen to reflect the words in Acts 17, \"These (Berea) were more noble than those in [[Thessalonica]] in that they received the word with all readiness of mind and searched the scriptures daily whether those things were so.\" Christadelphians, and Berean Christadelphians believe in the promises given to [[Abraham]], [[Isaac]], and [[David]] concerning the Kingdom of God. They deny the [[Doctrine of the Trinity]], a central tenet of orthodox [[Christianity]], and this refusal to recognize the triune nature of God has resulted in a major impasse between the Christadelphians/Berean Christadelphians and the Protestant, [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]], and [[Eastern Orthodox]] churches.\n\nSome groups among the [[Bible Student movement]] also adopted the name, such as the ''Berean Bible Students'' and the ''Berean Bible Institute''. Churches and institutions who adopt the Berean name, usually do so in order to express their desire to reflect the attitude of the Bereans in Acts 17, committing themselves to \"searching the scriptures daily.\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Eastons}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*\"Bereans\" and \"John Barclay\" in {{cite book | last = Livingstone | first = E. A., ed. | title = The Concise Oxford Dictionary of the Christian Church | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | location = [[London]] | year = 2006 | isbn = 978-0-19-861442-5 }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ccel.org/e/easton/ebd/ebd/T0000500.html#T0000530 Berea], [http://www.ccel.org/e/easton/ebd/ebd.html Easton's 1897 Bible Dictionary]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050422120441/http://bartleby.com/65/be/Bereans.html Bereans], [[The Columbia Encyclopedia]], Sixth Edition. 2001.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050205045220/http://www.catholic.com/thisrock/1997/9703fea3.asp Catholic Answers article]: \"Why the Bereans rejected ''[[sola scriptura]]''\"\n\n[[Category:Protestant denominations established in the 18th century]]\n[[Category:Presbyterianism in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Protestant denominations established in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Protestantism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Christian terminology]]\n", "text_old": "In ancient times, the '''Bereans''' were the inhabitants of the city of [[Berea (Bible)|Berea]], also known in the [[Bible]] as Beroea, and now known as [[Veria]] in what is today Greek Macedonia, [[Early centers of Christianity#Greece|northern Greece]]. The name has been taken up by certain [[Protestant]] groups.\n\n==Biblical context==\n\nAccording to the [[Book of Acts]], Chapter 17 verse 11, [[Paul of Tarsus]] and [[Silas]] preached at [[Berea (Bible)|Berea]], and the inhabitants \"... received the word with all readiness of mind, and searched the scriptures daily, whether those things were so.\",<ref>[http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=acts%2017:11&version=KJV Acts 17:11] [[King James Bible]]</ref> and many of them believed.\n\n==Modern use==\nHistorically, the Bereans (also called Beroeans, Barclayans or Barclayites) were a Protestant sect following former Scottish [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]] minister [[John Barclay (1734-1798)]]. Founded in [[Edinburgh]] in 1773, the Berean Church followed a modified form of [[Calvinism]]. It had congregations in [[Scotland]], [[London]] and [[Bristol]], but mainly merged with the [[Congregationalists#United Kingdom|Congregationalists]] after Barclay's death in 1798.\n\nA new Protestant Christian group began in the 1850s in the United States under the tutelage of Dr. John Thomas. The name \"[[Christadelphian]]\" was chosen as it is believed that those who believe and obey the [[Law of Christ|Commandments of Christ]] and the Bible as the inspired word of God, are \"Brethren in Christ\". The original group split, with one group continuing with the name \"The Christadelphians\" and the second group adding the word \"Berean\" to become the \"[[Berean Christadelphians]]\". The word \"Berean\" was chosen to reflect the words in Acts 17, \"These (Berea) were more noble than those in [[Thessalonica]] in that they received the word with all readiness of mind and searched the scriptures daily whether those things were so.\" Christadelphians, and Berean Christadelphians believe in the promises given to [[Abraham]], [[Isaac]], and [[David]] concerning the Kingdom of God. They deny the [[Doctrine of the Trinity]], a central tenet of orthodox [[Christianity]], and this refusal to recognize the triune nature of God has resulted in a major impasse between the Christadelphians/Berean Christadelphians and the Protestant, [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]], and [[Eastern Orthodox]] churches.\n\nSome groups among the [[Bible Student movement]] also adopted the name, such as the ''Berean Bible Students'' and the ''Berean Bible Institute''. Churches and institutions who adopt the Berean name, usually do so in order to express their desire to reflect the attitude of the Bereans in Acts 17, committing themselves to \"searching the scriptures daily.\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Eastons}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*\"Bereans\" and \"John Barclay\" in {{cite book | last = Livingstone | first = E. A., ed. | title = The Concise Oxford Dictionary of the Christian Church | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | location = [[London]] | year = 2006 | isbn = 978-0-19-861442-5 }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ccel.org/e/easton/ebd/ebd/T0000500.html#T0000530 Berea], [http://www.ccel.org/e/easton/ebd/ebd.html Easton's 1897 Bible Dictionary]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050422120441/http://bartleby.com/65/be/Bereans.html Bereans], [[The Columbia Encyclopedia]], Sixth Edition. 2001.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050205045220/http://www.catholic.com/thisrock/1997/9703fea3.asp Catholic Answers article]: \"Why the Bereans rejected ''[[sola scriptura]]''\"\n\n[[Category:Protestant denominations established in the 18th century]]\n[[Category:Presbyterianism in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Protestant denominations established in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Protestantism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Christian terminology]]\n", "name_user": "Prahlad balaji", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor grammatical fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bereans"}
{"title_page": "All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace", "text_new": "{{other uses|All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace (disambiguation)}}\n\"'''All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace'''\" is a poem by [[Richard Brautigan]] first published in his 1967 [[All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace (poetry collection)|collection of the same name]], his fifth book of poetry. It is an enthusiastic description of a [[technological utopianism|technological utopia]] in which machines improve and protect the lives of humans. It is Brautigan's most frequently reprinted poem.\n\n==Synopsis and analysis==\nBrautigan wrote the poem and eponymous collection between January 17-26, 2005, while a poet-in-residence at the [[California Institute of Technology]] in [[Pasadena, California]].<ref name=barbermachines/><ref name=watson/> The poem describes a [[technological utopia]] in which humans and technology work together for the greater good. Brautigan writes about \"[[mammal]]s and [[computer]]s liv[ing] together in mutually [[computer programming|programming]] harmony\", with technology acting as caretakers while \"we are free of our labors and joined back to nature.\"<ref name=madrigal/><ref name=bokinsky/> Reviewers disagree whether it should be taken earnestly or ironically.\n\nMost critics take the poem as a [[counterculture]], [[communitarian]] adoption of [[Cold War]]-era technological visions. Brautigan's publisher, Claude Hayward, said it \"caught me with its magical references to benign machines keeping order ... [which] fit right in with our optimism over the promise of the computer\".<ref name=barberbook/> In Vijay Nambisan's review for ''[[The Hindu]]'' in 2000, he said: \"You cannot write a poem like this today. It is too childlike, too innocent. Indeed, college friends who were moved by Brautigan's work twenty years ago would now laugh at me for choosing it. That's more or less what happened to Brautigan.\"<ref name=nambisan/>\n\nOthers have interpreted it as an ironic, mocking critique of the technologically enabled utopia it purports to long for.<ref name=chicagoreader/><ref name=turner/> According to [[Stanford University|Stanford]]'s Carlos Seligo, there is an irony in the poem that \"is as subtle and complex as his mixed metaphors\", which Seligo says are \"always doing at least three\u2014and often four, five, or six things at once.\"<ref name=seligo/> Robert J. Grangeware noted how unusual it is for [[American poetry|American poets]] to take a positive view of our relationship with technology, but if viewed as ironic it \"joins the mainstream of [[anti-technology|antitechnological]] American verse.\"<ref name=grangeware/>\n\n==Publication history==\nThe poem was first published by the Communication Company in 1967, type-written on an {{convert|8.5|by|11|in|mm|adj=on|0}} mimeographed broadside with both the title and imprint hand-written.<ref name=barbermachines/>\n\nIt was the title poem in the April 1967 [[All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace (collection)|collection of the same name]], published in April 1967. 1,500 copies of the 36-page work were printed at the Communication Company, and all were given away for free.<ref name=barbermachines/>\n\nIt was included with the rest of the contents of the 1967 collection, along with other previously published collections and new material, in ''[[The Pill versus the Springhill Mine Disaster]]'' (1968).<ref name=barberpill/>\n\nBrautigan gave the poem to [[The Diggers (theater)|The Diggers]] to include in their August 1968 pamphlet, ''The Digger Papers''. The 24-page pamphlet was published in ''[[The Realist]]'' issue 81, and another 40,000 copies were printed by the Diggers and given away for free.<ref name=barberwho/>\n\n\"All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace\" is Brautigan's most frequently reprinted poem.<ref name=barberbook/> In the original 1967 publication, Brautigan included a [[copyleft]] statement which retains copyright but grants permission to reprint any poem in ''All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace'' so long as it's given away for free.<ref name=barbermachines/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe documentary series ''[[All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace (TV series)|All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace]]'' was named after the poem, which is a favorite of director [[Adam Curtis]]. Its second part includes a recording of Brautigan doing a reading. According to the ''[[Chicago Reader]]'', \"For all the frenzy of the images, what dominates the sequence are Brautigan's voice and the languid piece of symphonic music on the soundtrack.\"<ref name=chicagoreader/>\n\nAt the [[Palais de Tokyo]], the poem inspired a show of the same name in 2017, curated by Yoann Gourmel. It began with a poster for the poem, and included works which ''Art in America''{{'}}s Federico Florian said superficially fulfill Brautigan's dreams, \"[evoking] a present tense where technology has imbued every aspect of human life, and therefore reshaped the mechanisms of our affections.\"<ref name=artinamerica/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=artinamerica>{{cite journal|work=Art in America|last=Florian|first=Federico|title=\"All Watched Over By Machines of Loving Grace\" - Palais de Tokyo|date=June 2017|pages=146|volume=105|issue=6}}</ref>\n<ref name=barberbook>{{cite book|last=Barber|first=John F.|title=Richard Brautigan: Essays on the Writings and Life|publisher=McFarland|date=2006|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MsXuel52NFsC|isbn=9780786482511}}</ref>\n<ref name=barbermachines>{{cite web|work=Brautigan.net|last=Barber|first=John F.|url=http://www.brautigan.net/machines.html|title=Poetry - All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace}}</ref>\n<ref name=barberpill>{{cite web|work=Brautigan.net |last=Barber |first=John F. |url=http://www.brautigan.net/pill.html |title=Poetry - The Pill versus The Springhill Mine Disaster |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114231634/http://www.brautigan.net/pill.html |archivedate=2009-01-14 }}</ref>\n<ref name=barberwho>{{cite web|work=Brautigan.net |last=Barber |first=John F. |url=http://www.brautigan.net/who.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060811204155/http://www.brautigan.net/who.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-08-11 |title=A-Z Index }}</ref>\n<ref name=bokinsky>{{cite book|last=Bokinsky|first=Caroline J.|section=Richard Brautigan|title=Dictionary of Literary Biography|volume=5|editor=Greiner, Donald J.|location=Detroit|publisher=Gale Research Company|date=1980|pages=96\u201399}}</ref>\n<ref name=chicagoreader>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2012/01/05/now-online-all-watched-over-by-machines-of-loving-grace-part-2|work=Chicago Reader|last=Sachs|first=Ben|date=5 January 2012|title=Now online: All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace (part 2)}}</ref>\n<ref name=grangeware>{{cite book|editor=Grangeware, Robert J.|title=The Exploited Eden: Literature on the American Environment|pages=376|location=New York|publisher=Harper and Row|date=1972}}</ref>\n<ref name=madrigal>{{cite web|work=The Atlantic|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2011/09/weekend-poem-all-watched-over-by-machines-of-loving-grace/245251/|title=Weekend Poem: All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace|last=Madrigal|first=Alexis C.|date=17 September 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=nambisan>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2000/06/03/stories/1303110d.htm|title=Pines and cybernetics|last=Nambisan|first=Vijay|date=3 June 2000|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404202754/http://www.thehindu.com/2000/06/03/stories/1303110d.htm|archive-date=4 April 2018|url-status=live|access-date=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n<ref name=seligo>{{cite web|url=https://web.stanford.edu/group/ats/cgi-bin/hivetalkin/?p=1637|work=Stanford University Libraries - Academic Technology Specialists|last=Seligo|first=Carlos|date=4 June 2011|title=\"All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace\"|access-date=3 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609121806/https://web.stanford.edu/group/ats/cgi-bin/hivetalkin/?p=1637|archive-date=9 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n<ref name=turner>{{cite book|pages=38\u201339|last=Turner|first=Fred|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2SNFpgX_WigC|publisher=University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago, IL|title=From Counterculture to Cyberculture: Stewart Brand, the Whole Earth Network, and the Rise of Digital Utopianism|date=2010|isbn=9780226817439}}</ref>\n<ref name=watson>{{cite book|pages=285-306|last=Watson|first=Ian|title=The Universal Machine|chapter=Machines of Loving Grace|publisher=Copernicus|isbn=978-3-642-28102-0|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-28102-0_13}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.brautigan.net/graphics/machines/machines-loudspeaker.gif Scanned copy of the first 1967 broadside]\n*[http://www.brautigan.net/machines.html ''All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace''] at Brautigan.net\n{{Richard Brautigan}}\n[[Category:Works by Richard Brautigan]]\n[[Category:1967 poems]]\n[[Category:Utopian fiction]]\n[[Category:American poems]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace (disambiguation)}}\n\"'''All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace'''\" is a poem by [[Richard Brautigan]] first published in his 1967 [[All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace (poetry collection)|collection of the same name]], his fifth book of poetry. It is an enthusiastic description of a [[technological utopianism|technological utopia]] in which machines improve and protect the lives of humans. It is Brautigan's most frequently reprinted poem.\n\n==Synopsis and analysis==\nBrautigan wrote the poem and eponymous collection between January 17-26, 1967, while a poet-in-residence at the [[California Institute of Technology]] in [[Pasadena, California]].<ref name=barbermachines/><ref name=watson/> The poem describes a [[technological utopia]] in which humans and technology work together for the greater good. Brautigan writes about \"[[mammal]]s and [[computer]]s liv[ing] together in mutually [[computer programming|programming]] harmony\", with technology acting as caretakers while \"we are free of our labors and joined back to nature.\"<ref name=madrigal/><ref name=bokinsky/> Reviewers disagree whether it should be taken earnestly or ironically.\n\nMost critics take the poem as a [[counterculture]], [[communitarian]] adoption of [[Cold War]]-era technological visions. Brautigan's publisher, Claude Hayward, said it \"caught me with its magical references to benign machines keeping order ... [which] fit right in with our optimism over the promise of the computer\".<ref name=barberbook/> In Vijay Nambisan's review for ''[[The Hindu]]'' in 2000, he said: \"You cannot write a poem like this today. It is too childlike, too innocent. Indeed, college friends who were moved by Brautigan's work twenty years ago would now laugh at me for choosing it. That's more or less what happened to Brautigan.\"<ref name=nambisan/>\n\nOthers have interpreted it as an ironic, mocking critique of the technologically enabled utopia it purports to long for.<ref name=chicagoreader/><ref name=turner/> According to [[Stanford University|Stanford]]'s Carlos Seligo, there is an irony in the poem that \"is as subtle and complex as his mixed metaphors\", which Seligo says are \"always doing at least three\u2014and often four, five, or six things at once.\"<ref name=seligo/> Robert J. Grangeware noted how unusual it is for [[American poetry|American poets]] to take a positive view of our relationship with technology, but if viewed as ironic it \"joins the mainstream of [[anti-technology|antitechnological]] American verse.\"<ref name=grangeware/>\n\n==Publication history==\nThe poem was first published by the Communication Company in 1967, type-written on an {{convert|8.5|by|11|in|mm|adj=on|0}} mimeographed broadside with both the title and imprint hand-written.<ref name=barbermachines/>\n\nIt was the title poem in the April 1967 [[All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace (collection)|collection of the same name]], published in April 1967. 1,500 copies of the 36-page work were printed at the Communication Company, and all were given away for free.<ref name=barbermachines/>\n\nIt was included with the rest of the contents of the 1967 collection, along with other previously published collections and new material, in ''[[The Pill versus the Springhill Mine Disaster]]'' (1968).<ref name=barberpill/>\n\nBrautigan gave the poem to [[The Diggers (theater)|The Diggers]] to include in their August 1968 pamphlet, ''The Digger Papers''. The 24-page pamphlet was published in ''[[The Realist]]'' issue 81, and another 40,000 copies were printed by the Diggers and given away for free.<ref name=barberwho/>\n\n\"All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace\" is Brautigan's most frequently reprinted poem.<ref name=barberbook/> In the original 1967 publication, Brautigan included a [[copyleft]] statement which retains copyright but grants permission to reprint any poem in ''All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace'' so long as it's given away for free.<ref name=barbermachines/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe documentary series ''[[All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace (TV series)|All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace]]'' was named after the poem, which is a favorite of director [[Adam Curtis]]. Its second part includes a recording of Brautigan doing a reading. According to the ''[[Chicago Reader]]'', \"For all the frenzy of the images, what dominates the sequence are Brautigan's voice and the languid piece of symphonic music on the soundtrack.\"<ref name=chicagoreader/>\n\nAt the [[Palais de Tokyo]], the poem inspired a show of the same name in 2017, curated by Yoann Gourmel. It began with a poster for the poem, and included works which ''Art in America''{{'}}s Federico Florian said superficially fulfill Brautigan's dreams, \"[evoking] a present tense where technology has imbued every aspect of human life, and therefore reshaped the mechanisms of our affections.\"<ref name=artinamerica/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=artinamerica>{{cite journal|work=Art in America|last=Florian|first=Federico|title=\"All Watched Over By Machines of Loving Grace\" - Palais de Tokyo|date=June 2017|pages=146|volume=105|issue=6}}</ref>\n<ref name=barberbook>{{cite book|last=Barber|first=John F.|title=Richard Brautigan: Essays on the Writings and Life|publisher=McFarland|date=2006|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MsXuel52NFsC|isbn=9780786482511}}</ref>\n<ref name=barbermachines>{{cite web|work=Brautigan.net|last=Barber|first=John F.|url=http://www.brautigan.net/machines.html|title=Poetry - All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace}}</ref>\n<ref name=barberpill>{{cite web|work=Brautigan.net |last=Barber |first=John F. |url=http://www.brautigan.net/pill.html |title=Poetry - The Pill versus The Springhill Mine Disaster |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114231634/http://www.brautigan.net/pill.html |archivedate=2009-01-14 }}</ref>\n<ref name=barberwho>{{cite web|work=Brautigan.net |last=Barber |first=John F. |url=http://www.brautigan.net/who.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060811204155/http://www.brautigan.net/who.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-08-11 |title=A-Z Index }}</ref>\n<ref name=bokinsky>{{cite book|last=Bokinsky|first=Caroline J.|section=Richard Brautigan|title=Dictionary of Literary Biography|volume=5|editor=Greiner, Donald J.|location=Detroit|publisher=Gale Research Company|date=1980|pages=96\u201399}}</ref>\n<ref name=chicagoreader>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2012/01/05/now-online-all-watched-over-by-machines-of-loving-grace-part-2|work=Chicago Reader|last=Sachs|first=Ben|date=5 January 2012|title=Now online: All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace (part 2)}}</ref>\n<ref name=grangeware>{{cite book|editor=Grangeware, Robert J.|title=The Exploited Eden: Literature on the American Environment|pages=376|location=New York|publisher=Harper and Row|date=1972}}</ref>\n<ref name=madrigal>{{cite web|work=The Atlantic|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2011/09/weekend-poem-all-watched-over-by-machines-of-loving-grace/245251/|title=Weekend Poem: All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace|last=Madrigal|first=Alexis C.|date=17 September 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=nambisan>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2000/06/03/stories/1303110d.htm|title=Pines and cybernetics|last=Nambisan|first=Vijay|date=3 June 2000|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404202754/http://www.thehindu.com/2000/06/03/stories/1303110d.htm|archive-date=4 April 2018|url-status=live|access-date=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n<ref name=seligo>{{cite web|url=https://web.stanford.edu/group/ats/cgi-bin/hivetalkin/?p=1637|work=Stanford University Libraries - Academic Technology Specialists|last=Seligo|first=Carlos|date=4 June 2011|title=\"All Watched Over by Machines of Loving Grace\"|access-date=3 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609121806/https://web.stanford.edu/group/ats/cgi-bin/hivetalkin/?p=1637|archive-date=9 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n<ref name=turner>{{cite book|pages=38\u201339|last=Turner|first=Fred|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2SNFpgX_WigC|publisher=University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago, IL|title=From Counterculture to Cyberculture: Stewart Brand, the Whole Earth Network, and the Rise of Digital Utopianism|date=2010|isbn=9780226817439}}</ref>\n<ref name=watson>{{cite book|pages=285-306|last=Watson|first=Ian|title=The Universal Machine|chapter=Machines of Loving Grace|publisher=Copernicus|isbn=978-3-642-28102-0|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-28102-0_13}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.brautigan.net/graphics/machines/machines-loudspeaker.gif Scanned copy of the first 1967 broadside]\n*